{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":68,"record_hash":"sha256:430534d0057480176eef972898e72e83b9fad058f53dab6ee3e7bcf0821805e5","timestamp":"2026-05-07T10:51:08.626Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 5c161a\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1112\nOutput:\n# Spec Iteration Process\n\nThis page defines how to improve the Agent Session Capture spec before using it\nas an implementation prompt.\n\nThe goal is not to make the docs bigger. The goal is to make the first\nimplementation hard to misread, hard to overbuild, and hard to steer into a bad\narchitecture.\n\n## Objective\n\nBefore writing code, the spec should be good enough that a coding agent can\nproduce a small first POC patch without guessing core behavior.\n\nA good spec answers:\n\n- What exactly is in the first patch?\n- What is explicitly out of scope?\n- What data is written, where, and under which keys?\n- What are the privacy defaults?\n- What is the CLI contract?\n- What tests prove the POC works?\n- What mistakes should the implementation avoid?\n\n## Review Loop\n\nUse this loop when changing the spec:\n\n1. **Scope pass** — is the POC still narrow?\n2. **Privacy pass** — could this capture or publish sensitive data by accident?\n3. **Architecture pass** — does this fit GitButler and GitMeta without dragging\n   in legacy or unrelated crates?\n4. **Implementation-prompt pass** — would Codex know exactly what to build and\n   test?\n5. **Synthesis pass** — update docs with the smallest changes that reduce\n   ambiguity.\n6. **Consistency pass** — check that README, requirements, architecture,\n   workflow, data model, and implementation contract do not contradict each\n   other.\n\nSub-agents are useful for steps 1–4 because each pass benefits from a narrow\nlens. The synthesis pass should be one coherent edit, not a merge of four voices.\n\n## Spec Quality Bar\n\nThe spec is ready to feed to Codex only when all of these are true:\n\n- POC scope is explicit and fits in one first patch.\n- Every future idea is clearly labelled as future/non-POC.\n- Transcript capture default is decided.\n- Serialization/push behavior is decided.\n- CLI flags, defaults, output fields, and failure behavior are specified.\n- GitMeta write keys an\n[TRUNCATED]\name POC scope.\n- [ ] `requirements-and-goals.md` separates POC goals from later goals.\n- [ ] `architecture.md` says what to implement now and what not to implement.\n- [ ] `capture-workflow.md` has exact first-pass CLI behavior.\n- [ ] `gitmeta-data-model.md` has a precise write table.\n- [ ] There is no unresolved contradiction around raw transcripts.\n- [ ] There is no unresolved contradiction around `--serialize`.\n- [ ] The acceptance tests can be implemented without inventing behavior.\n\n## Recommended Reviewer Prompts\n\n### Scope/Product Review\n\nReview this spec as a product/POC scope reviewer. Identify what criteria must be\ntrue before it is good enough to feed to Codex for implementation. Flag broad,\nambiguous, privacy-risky, or tangent-prone parts. Return acceptance criteria,\ntop risks, and concrete doc changes.\n\n### Architecture Review\n\nReview this spec as a Rust/GitButler architecture reviewer. Inspect GitButler and\nGitMeta APIs as needed. Flag bad dependency choices, legacy coupling, wrong CLI\nintegration, GitMeta misuse, and implementation traps. Return architecture\nacceptance criteria, traps, and concrete doc changes.\n\n### Privacy Review\n\nReview this spec as a privacy/security reviewer. Focus on transcript capture,\nlocal GitMeta storage, serialization/push boundaries, accidental capture,\nsecrets, and defaults. Return privacy acceptance criteria, blockers, and concrete\ndoc changes.\n\n### Implementation-Prompt Review\n\nReview this spec as if it will be pasted into Codex to implement the first POC.\nFocus on whether it is unambiguous, scoped, testable, and likely to produce a\nsmall correct patch. Return a prompt-readiness rubric, unclear details, and\nconcrete doc changes.\n\n## Change Discipline\n\nWhen updating the spec:\n\n- Preserve future ideas, but move them under future/non-POC sections.\n- Prefer tables and checklists over vague prose.\n- Resolve contradictions immediately; do not leave competing options unlabeled.\n- Add exact examples when a coding agent would otherwise guess.\n- Keep the first POC boring.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T10:51:08.626Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}